  "prompt": "Is it a felony to launder money?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is a serious criminal offense and is classified as a felony in the United States and many other jurisdictions. Money laundering involves disguising the origins of illegally obtained money, typically by means of transfers involving foreign banks or legitimate businesses. The crime is often associated with other illegal activities such as drug trafficking, fraud, and organized crime.\n\nIn the United States, the primary law governing money laundering is the **Money Laundering Control Act of 1986** (18 U.S.C. \u00a7\u00a7 1956 and 1957). Key aspects of this law include:\n\n1. **18 U.S.C. \u00a7 1956**: Prohibits transactions involving proceeds of unlawful activities with the intent to promote illegal activity, conceal the nature of the proceeds, or evade taxes.\n2. **18 U.S.C. \u00a7 1957**: Prohibits spending or depositing more than $10,000 of criminally derived proceeds in a financial institution.\n\nPenalties for money laundering can include:\n- Significant fines (up to $500,000 or twice the value of the laundered funds).\n- Imprisonment (up to 20 years per count, and potentially more if terrorism is involved).\n- Forfeiture of assets involved in or derived from the illegal activity.\n\nMoney laundering is also a crime internationally, with many countries having their own laws and cooperating through organizations like the **Financial Action Task Force (FATF)** to combat it.",
